You might be wondering why many schools only teach us to use smaller brushes, like number 8 or number 10. There has been a claim that using the smaller can assist in preventing overexposure. The statement isn’t 100% accurate. 
Don’t always turn to books for the answer, as the old saying.
If this is true then why aren’t all licensed manicurists using smaller brush at the nail salon? Using a smaller brush will require you to spend more time covering the full nail. You cannot do anything less than 3 beads with a size 8 brush. In some cases, you might need 4 to 5 beads. Using a large brush size 12, 14, 16, or 18 will enable you to apply beads much more rapidly than if you were to use a small brush. This will save you a great deal of time. As a result, your nails will be smoother and require less filing.

Q&A: While in use, will this Art & Artist LED Table Lamp cure gel polish?
The Art & Artist LED Light System is not designed to cure gel nail polish. Its primary function is to provide natural daylight illumination, similar to sunlight, for various purposes such as reading, crafting, and applying makeup. This lamp does not emit any harmful UV radiation and is not optimized for curing gel polish.
In contrast, LED gel polish cure lamps are specifically designed for curing gel nail polish, emitting a narrow range of light typically in the range of 365-405 nm, which activates the photoinitiators in the gel polish for quick hardening and curing.
The main difference between LED daylight lamps and LED gel polish cure lamps is their intended use, with LED Table Lamps being suitable for general lighting purposes and LED gel polish cure lamps designed specifically for curing gel nail polish.

Acrylic application is an important skill for nail technicians and is crucial to delivering high-quality nail sets that are appreciated by clients. Accurate and precise application is essential to save time and achieve consistent results. However, achieving accuracy and precision can be challenging, especially when it comes to understanding the powder to liquid ratio.

Unfortunately, there are some individuals in the industry who may falsely claim to be experts and provide free advice on precise application without having a proper understanding of the process. 

 When it comes to acrylic application, it’s important to be careful of false educators who may provide inaccurate advice. One way to spot these individuals is to observe the paper towel after acrylics have been applied
- If the paper towel is not relatively clean, it may indicate that too much waste acrylic and liquid were used during the application process. This can lead to less-than-perfect results and wasted product. Be sure to choose an experienced and reputable educator for consistent, high-quality results every time. By doing so, you’ll be on your way to becoming a skilled and successful nail technician.
